05481nam a22008895i 9783110220810DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)774092805  a97831102208107 a10.1515/97831102208102doi  a(DE-B1597)36962  a(OCoLC)647843543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB626.T54bC58 2009eb 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a186/.12221 aClayman, Dee L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTimon of Phlius :bPyrrhonism into Poetry /cDee L. Clayman. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (261 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aUntersuchungen zur antiken Literatur und Geschichte ,x1862-1112 ;v9800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1 - The Lives of Timon and Pyrrho -- tChapter 2 - Timon and Pyrrho: The Pytho and the Indalmoi -- tChapter 3 - Timon's Silloi: Organization and Principle Fragments -- tChapter 4 - The Silloi in its Literary Context -- tChapter 5 - Timon's Reception in Hellenistic Literature -- tChapter 6 - Skepticism in Hellenistic Literature -- tConclusion - An Aesthetics of Skepticism -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly Skepticism and its founder, Pyrrho of Elis, were introduced to the world in the third century BCE by the poet and philosopher Timon of Phlius. This is the first book-length study in English of the fragments of Timon’s works. Of his more than 100 titles, four fragments remain of a catalogue elegy, the Indalmoi, and 133 verses of the Silloi, a hexameter parody in three books in which Timon ridicules philosophers of all periods whom he observes on a trip to Hades. Dee L. Clayman reconstructs the books of the Silloi starting from an outline in Diogenes Laertius and the book numbers assigned to a few fragments by their sources. This has not been attempted since Wachsmuth’s edition of 1885, and carries his approach further by careful observation of syntactic and contextual clues in the text. Using the Greek text of Lloyd-Jones and Parsons of 1983, all of the extant fragments are translated into English and discussed as literature, rather than as source material for the history of philosophy. Separate chapters demonstrate that the principle Hellenistic poets, Callimachus, Theocritus and Apollonius of Rhodes, were aware of Timon’s work specifically, and of Skepticism generally. The book concludes with a definition of “Skeptical aesthetics” that places many of the characteristic features of Hellenistic literature in a skeptical milieu.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aSkeptics (Greek philosophy). 4aPyrrho von Elis (Philosoph). 4aSkeptizismus. 4aTimon von Phlius (Philosoph). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aPyrrho of Elis (philosopher).  aSkepticism.  aTimon of Phlius (philosopher).08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Classics and Near East Studies 2000-2014 (EN)z978311062109908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2009z9783110219517oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2009z978311021952408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET PHILOSOPHIE UND GESCHICHTE 2009z9783110219500oZDB-23-DGE0 cprintz978311022080340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311022081040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110220810423Coveruhttps://www.de